San Diego Burrito Dataset

Who doesnt like a good burrito, amirite? I thought so. Well thanks to Scott Cole we have an awesome dataset of a bunch of burritos in San Diego. What can we learn about a burrito from this data? So much! First, what did we get in this data?

So much good stuff here. There is some ambiguity in the naming conventions here, specifically variables like Ham, Clinantro, and Salsa are categorical not continuous, in this case present or absent. Adding the prefix has helps me keep things straight and also well recode the (,x) to (0,1) and get rid of some NAs that crept in there. Well also drop hasQueso as there arent any data points in there and I found it just cause me headache in the analysis as well, and finally some non-sensical rows at the end that excel kindly privided for us.

colnames(burritoData)[32:66] <- paste("has", colnames(burritoData[,c(32:66)]), sep = "")
burritoData[,32:66] <- lapply(burritoData[,32:66], factor, levels = c("", "x"), labels = c(0,1))
burritoData <- subset(burritoData, select = -c(hasQueso))
burritoData <- subset(burritoData[1:382,])
ls(burritoData)

To answer the age old question, What makes a great burrito, lets run a random forest simulation on the data to pick out the ingredients most highly influencing the Overall rating of a burrito. I should mention that the ingredients component of the dataset is a bit funky in that its not complete, so doing the analysis can cause problems particularly if you use a training set and it happens to grab a variable with limited n-size and it depletes the observations and we cant then compare the results against the test-set. In this case, because its a burrito, were good, just an FYI. Well also subset here to just handle the ingredients to make the process clearer.

# a 200 datapoint training set
ingredients <- burritoData[,c(26,32:65)]
ingredients[is.na(ingredients)] <- 0
#train<-sample(1:nrow(ingredients),200)
burritoForest=randomForest(overall ~ . , data = ingredients)
plot(burritoForest)

varImpPlot(burritoForest)

burritoForest
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = overall ~ ., data = ingredients) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 11
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 0.6489977
##                     % Var explained: -0.62

Yeah, nothing surprisng here. Looks to me like a Chicken burrito with beans, guac, pico, rice, cheese, and sauce is a pretty stellar combo. Yes, I know guac is extra.

Yelp and Google

Im also curious how a burritos rating relates to the restaurant rating, in this case from Yelp and Google.

scatterPlot<-ggplot(burritoData) +
  geom_point(aes(x=Google,y=overall), colour='#56B4E9') +
  geom_point(aes(x=Yelp, y=overall), colour="red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x ="Google - Blue, Yelp - Red")
scatterPlot

yelp<-lm(overall~Yelp, data=burritoData)
google<-lm(overall~Google, data=burritoData)
sjt.lm(yelp,google)
## Fitted models have different coefficients. Grouping may not work properly. Set `group.pred = FALSE` if you encouter cluttered labelling.
overall overall
B CI p B CI p
(Intercept) 2.29 1.063.53 <.001 1.64 0.003.27 .050
Yelp 0.29 -0.030.60 .075
Google 0.42 0.040.81 .033
Observations 82 82
R2 / adj. R2 .039 / .027 .056 / .044

Thats pretty interesting, Yelp rating is barely insignificant, while Google is more significantly correlated. Just goes to show you, never rule out the potential value of a burrito!

Sweet mexican goodness, whos hungry? This guy. Thats actually a nice seque into something I was curious about: Whats the influence of relative hunger on the rating of a burrito?

hungerLm<-lm(overall~Hunger,burritoData)
sjp.lm(hungerLm)

sjt.lm(hungerLm)
overall
B CI p
(Intercept) 3.06 2.723.40 <.001
Hunger 0.15 0.060.25 .002
Observations 377
R2 / adj. R2 .026 / .024

Yikes. I cant say Im surprised here either burritos look good when youre not hungry, imagine how good they are when you are!
